<section xml:id="section-using-technology-to-explore-functions">

    <title>Using Technology to Explore Functions</title>

    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li><xref ref="mth95-calculator-skills" /></li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <introduction>
         <p>Graphing technology can be used to explore the properties of functions more in-depth than we could otherwise do. It can help us quickly create a table of values, as well as quickly create the graph of a function. Such technology can also be used to evaluate functions, determine where a given function value occurs, find maximum and minimum values, and explore other key features.</p>

         <p>There are many graphing technologies currently available, including (but not limited to): physical (hand-held) graphing calculators, <url href="https://www.desmos.com/">Desmos</url>, <url href="https://www.geogebra.org/">GeoGebra</url>, and <url href="http://www.wolframalpha.com/">Wolframalpha</url>.</p>

         <p>This section will focus on <em>how</em> technology can be used to explore functions and their key features. Although the choice of particular graphing technology varies by each school and curriculum, the key ways in which it is used to explore functions is independent of the actual technology or tool and can be done with each of the technologies listed above.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube=""/>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Finding an Appropriate Window</title>

        <p>To view the graph of a simple linear function like <m>y=2x+5</m>, most any graphing technology will by default show this graph in a good window. (A common default window often goes from <m>x=-10</m> to <m>x=10</m> and <m>y=-10</m> to <m>y=10</m>). What if we wanted to graph something with a much larger magnitude though, such as <m>y=2000x+5000</m>? If we tried to view this for <m>x=-10</m> to <m>x=10</m> and <m>y=-10</m> to <m>y=10</m>, the function wouldn't even appear. We know why though, as this function is familiar. As a linear function, we know that its slope is <m>2{,}000</m> and that it has a <m>y</m>-intercept of <m>(0,5000)</m>. So none of its function values are in that window.</p>

