    <p>Now let's practice finding an appropriate viewing window with a less familiar function.</p>
    <example>
        <p>Find an appropriate window for <m>q(x)=\frac{x^3}{100}-2x+1</m>.</p>
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
            <p>Entering this function into graphing technology, we input <c>q(x)=(x^3)/100-2x+1</c>. A default window will generally give us something like this:</p>

            <figure xml:id="figure-function-in-default-window">
                <caption>Function <m>q</m> graphed in the default window.</caption>
                <image>
                    <description></description>
                    <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xmin=-10,xmax=10,
                            ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                            xtick={-8,-6,...,8},
                            minor xtick={-9,-7,...,9},
                            ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                            minor ytick={-9,-7,...,9}
                                ]
                                \addplot+[domain=-10:10,-,samples=100] {(x^3)/100-2*x+1};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">        
            <p>We can tell from the lower right corner of <xref ref="figure-function-in-default-window">Figure</xref> that we're not quite viewing all of the important details of this function. To determine a better window, we could use technology to make a table of values. Another more rudimentary option though is to just double the viewing constraints for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, as shown in <xref ref="figure-function-in-doubled-window">Figure</xref>.</p>

            <figure xml:id="figure-function-in-doubled-window">
                <caption>Function <m>q</m> graphed in an expanded window.</caption>
                <image>
                    <description></description>
                    <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xmin=-20,xmax=20,
                            ymin=-20,ymax=20,
                            xtick={-16,-12,...,16},
                            minor xtick={-19,-18,...,19},
                            ytick={-16,-12,...,16},
                            minor ytick={-19,-18,...,19}
                                ]
                                \addplot+[domain=-20:20,-,samples=100] {(x^3)/100-2*x+1};
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        </sidebyside>
    </example>
</subsection>

<subsection>
    <title>Using Technology to Determine Key Features of a Graph</title>

        <p>The key features of a graph can be determined using graphing technology. Here, we'll show how to determine the <m>x</m>-intercepts, <m>y</m>-intercepts, maximum/minimum values, and the domain and range using technology.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
            <p>Graph the function given by <m>p(x)=-1000x^2-100x+40</m>. Determine an appropriate viewing window, and then use graphing technology to determine the following:
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Find the <m>x</m>-intercepts of the function.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Determine the <m>y</m>-intercept of the function.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Determine the maximum function value and where it occurs.</p></li>
                    <li><p>State the domain and range of this function.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <figure>
                    <caption></caption>
                    <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                    <p>To start, we'll take a quick view of this function in a default window. We can see that we need to zoom in on the <m>x</m>-values, but we need to zoom out on the <m>y</m>-values.</p>

                    <figure xml:id="figure-graph-with-default-windwo-needs-small-increments">
                        <caption>Graph of <m>y=p(x)</m> in an appropriate window</caption>
                            <image>
                                <description></description>
                                <latex-image>
                                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                        \begin{axis}[xmin=-10,xmax=10,
                                        ymin=-10,ymax=10,
                                        xtick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                        minor xtick={-9.5,-9,...,9.5},
                                        ytick={-8,-6,...,8},
                                        minor ytick={-9.5,-9,...,9.5}
                                            ]
                                            \addplot+[domain=-0.5:0.5,samples=100] {-1000*x^2-100*x+40};
                                        \end{axis}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                    ]]>
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                    </figure>
                    </sidebyside>
                </figure>

                <p>We need <m>x</m>-values from <m>-0.5</m> to <m>0.5</m>, so we will look at <m>x</m>-values in that window in increments of <m>0.1</m>, as shown in <xref ref="table-values-for-an-appropriate-window-small-increments">Table</xref>. This table allows us to determine an appropriate viewing window for <m>y=p(x)</m> which is shown in <xref ref="figure-graph-with-appropriate-window-small-increments">Figure</xref>.</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Creating a table of values to determine an appropriate graphing window</caption>
                    <sidebyside widths="30% 64%" margins="0%">        
                    <table xml:id="table-values-for-an-appropriate-window-small-increments">
                        <caption>Function values for <m>y=p(x)</m></caption>
                        <tabular>
                            <col halign="center" right="minor"/>
                            <col halign="center" />
                            <row bottom="medium">
                                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>p(x)</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-0.5</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-160</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-0.4</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-80</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-0.3</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-20</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-0.2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>20</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>-0.1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>40</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>40</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0.1</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>20</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0.2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-20</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0.3</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-80</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0.4</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-160</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>0.5</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>-260</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                    <figure xml:id="figure-graph-with-appropriate-window-small-increments">
                            <caption>Graph of <m>y=p(x)</m> in an appropriate window showing key features</caption>
                            <image>
                                <description></description>
                                <latex-image>
                                    <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                        \begin{axis}[xmin=-0.5,xmax=0.5,
                                        ymin=-60,ymax=60,
                                        xtick={-0.4,-0.3,...,0.4},
                                        minor xtick={-0.4,-0.3,...,0.4},
                                        ytick={-40,-20,...,40},
                                        minor ytick={-50,-40,...,50}
                                            ]
                                            \addplot+[domain=-0.5:0.5,samples=100] {-1000*x^2-100*x+40};
                                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-0.2562,0)} node[left]{$(-0.2562,0)$};;
                                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0.1562,0)} node[right]{$(0.1562,0)$};;
                                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,40)} node[right]{$(0,40)$};;
                                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-0.05,42.5)} node[above]{$(-0.05,42.5)$};;
                                        \end{axis}
                                    \end{tikzpicture}
                                    ]]>
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
                    </sidebyside>
                </figure>                

                <p>We can now use <xref ref="figure-graph-with-appropriate-window-small-increments">Figure</xref> to determine the <m>x</m>-intercepts, the <m>y</m>-intercept, the maximum function value, and the domain and range.</p>

                <p><ol>
                    <li><p>To determine the <m>x</m>-intercepts, we will find the points where <m>y</m> is zero. These are <m>(-0.2562,0)</m> and <m>(0.1562,0)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>To determine the <m>y</m>-intercept, we need the point where <m>x</m> is zero. This point is <m>(0,40)</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>The highest point on the graph is the vertex, which is <m>(-0.05,42.5)</m>. So the maximum function value is <m>42.5</m> and occurs at <m>-0.05</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>We can see that the function is defined for all <m>x</m>-values, so the domain is <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>. The maximum function value is <m>42.5</m>, and there is no minimum function value. Thus the range is <m>(-\infty,42.5]</m>.</p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    <warning>
        <!--https://www.desmos.com/calculator/3doxbb3l89-->
        <p>If we use graphing technology to graph the function <m>g(x) = 0.0002x^2 + 0.00146x + 0.00266</m>, we may be mislead by the way values are rounded. Without technology, we know that this function is a quadratic function and therefore has at most two <m>x</m>-intercepts and has a vertex that will determine the minimum function value.</p>

        <p>However, using technology we could obtain a graph with the following key points:</p>
            <figure xml:id="figure-graph-with-rounding-issue">
                <caption>Misleading graph</caption>
                <image>
                    <description></description>
                    <latex-image>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xmin=-4,xmax=8,
                            ymin=-0.04,ymax=0.04,
                            xtick={-2,0,...,6},
                            ytick={-0.03,-0.02,...,0.03}
                                ]
                                \addplot+[domain=-4:8] {0.0002*x^2 + 0.00146*x + 0.00266};
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3.8,0)} node[left]{$(-3.8,0)$};;
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3.65,0)} node[above]{$(-3.65,0)$};;
                                \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(-3.5,0)} node[right]{$(-3.5,0)$};;
                            \end{axis}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        ]]>
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>

        <p>This <em>looks</em> like there are three <m>x</m>-intercepts, which we know is not possible for a quadratic function. We can evaluate <m>g</m> at <m>x=-3.85</m> and determine that <m>g(-3.65)= 0.000045</m>, which is <em>approximately</em> zero when rounded. So the true vertex of this function is <m>(-3.85,-0.000045)</m>, and the minimum value of this function is <m>-0.000045</m> (not zero).</p>
        <p>Every graphing tool generally has some type of limitation like this one, and it's good to be aware that these limitations exist.</p>
    </warning>

</subsection>

